  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Providing Cardiac Medical Care to poor and IDP patients in Homs</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Al Afia Charity Fund is one of the main NGOs in Homs governorate. It provides health operation services by referring cases to Al Shawi private hospital and Al Birr hospital in Al-Waer HTR area that belong to (Al Birr social services and Al Afia Charity Fund). These hospitals were especially prepared for this project services, to get the needed treatment and cover the costs. Doctors or other associations refer Patients to the NGO, where they go through a committee to check the eligibility of the patient to access the services.

This committee is not medical it is for Social Survey. It studies the patient social situation, number of children, monthly income, residence ,and number of productive members to insure that the patient is in need and deserves the association help while the medical opinion comes from the doctor or the hospital that receives the patient.

Although the committee isn&apos;t medical it studies the feedback given by the patients .It looks into the doctors medical history, and it monitors the patients development after the surgery. Even though  there isn&apos;t  a wide range of doctors to choose from in Homs.  

The patient should provide a medical report explaining his/her situation. When the patient is eligible for having the cardiac catheterization diagnoses or surgeries the NGO refers him/her to Al Shawi new hospital.
There is a follow up committee to Keep track of the patient&apos;s condition in the hospital, and make sure of the surgery.   
Al Afia Fund Charity covers all needed referrals from the city and rural areas and accepts all Syrians patients coming from other governorate.
Al Afia Fund Charity Sponsors ambulatory injuries received by Homs&apos; hospitals and from hot spots around it.
AFIA is the only specialized NGO exclusively in health services in Homs governorate and plays a major role in the coordination between National NGOs in the governorate, while other NGOs only provide health services temporarily ( in case of funding )</narrative>
  </description>
